## 4. Module Communication Matrix

Core rule: **data flows strictly downstream through the layer boundaries already frozen; no layer may reach backward or skip forward.** The table below governs cross-layer and cross-module reads.

| Module | May Read | May NOT Read |
|---|---|---|
| Selection Engine | Raw market/session data | Anything from Layers 1–4 |
| Context Snapshot | Selection Engine output (SelectionResult) | Structural/Sweep Validation, Strategies, Arbitration |
| Structural Validation | Context Snapshot | Sweep Validation's internal state, Strategy layer, Arbitration |
| Sweep Validation | Context Snapshot | Structural Validation's internal state, Strategy layer, Arbitration |
| Market Context | Structural Validation + Sweep Validation outputs only | Raw Context Snapshot directly (must go through the two Validation modules, not around them), Strategy layer |
| ValidationSummary (contract, not a module) | — | — |
| Strategy Registry | Static strategy definitions/config | ValidationSummary, market data (registry is metadata-only) |
| Strategy Context Enrichment | ValidationSummary + Strategy Registry metadata | Individual Strategy internals, StrategyResult, Arbitration |
| Strategy Router | Enriched Strategy Context, Strategy Registry (eligibility rules) | StrategyResult (routing happens before results exist), Arbitration logic |
| Strategies | Only their own enriched StrategyContext | Other strategies' contexts or results, Arbitration, Recommendation, Risk |
| Arbitration Engine | StrategyResult[] (all of them, read-only) | Raw ValidationSummary, Context Snapshot, or any Layer 0/1 internals directly — it must reason only over StrategyResult[] |
| EntryRecommendation Builder | ArbitrationResult only | Anything else — this is the frozen 1:1 rule; even ValidationSummary must not leak in here |
| **Risk Layer (future)** | EntryRecommendation, account state, prop-firm config, open-position state | Strategies, Arbitration internals, ValidationSummary — Risk must be able to evaluate any EntryRecommendation without knowing *how* it was derived |
| **Execution Authorization (future)** | Risk Layer's decision, broker/session state | Strategies, Arbitration, raw market analysis |
| **Trade Manager (future)** | Live position state, Execution Layer confirmations | Selection/Analysis/Strategy layers directly — must react to price/time and its own position state only |
| **Broker/MT5 adapter (future)** | Execution/Trade Manager commands | Anything above Execution — the broker adapter should be the "dumbest" module in the system |
| **Event Log (future, cross-cutting)** | Read-only subscriber to every contract at every boundary | Nothing writes back into it except appends; it must never be queried *by* upstream layers to influence decisions (that would create a hidden feedback loop) |
| **Performance Analytics (future)** | Event Log / closed-trade records only | Live Strategies/Arbitration/Risk — analytics must be strictly offline/downstream so it can never accidentally influence a live decision path |

**Key architectural rule to carry forward:** the Event Log is a **sink**, never a **source**, for the live decision path. Analytics reads from history; nothing in the live path reads from Analytics. This prevents a very common institutional-system bug where "smart" feedback loops (e.g., a strategy quietly adjusting itself based on its own recent performance) bypass Risk and Arbitration entirely.

