## 5. Contract Review

Reviewing each immutable contract for long-term maintainability gaps. All additions below are **additive/optional fields** — none require breaking existing frozen structures.

| Contract | Adequate As-Is? | Recommended Additions (non-breaking) |
|---|---|---|
| SelectionResult | Mostly | `selectionTimestamp`, `selectionId` (for event-log correlation) |
| ContextSnapshot | Mostly | `snapshotId`, `sourceDataVersion` (which feed/version produced this — matters once you have multiple brokers/data sources) |
| ValidationSummary | Mostly | `validationId`, back-reference `snapshotId` (for audit-trail traceability) |
| StrategyContext | Mostly | `strategyId`, `contextId` |
| StrategyResult | **Gap** | Add `confidence`/`strength` score (optional, strategy-populated) if not already present — without this, Arbitration can only do rule-based conflict resolution, never weighted/ranked resolution, which will matter as strategy count grows (§7). Also add `strategyVersion` (so Analytics can distinguish results from Strategy v1 vs v2 of the same strategy id). |
| ArbitrationResult | **Gap** | Add `rejectedCandidates` (the StrategyResult[] that lost, with a short reason code each) — this is cheap to add now and becomes extremely valuable for Performance Analytics and for debugging "why didn't Strategy X fire even though its conditions looked right." Without this field, that information is lost forever the moment Arbitration completes. |
| EntryRecommendation | Mostly | `recommendationId`, `arbitrationResultId` (traceability chain back through every contract) — required once the Risk Layer needs to log *why* a decision was made, and required for the Event Log (§3.5) to be genuinely queryable end-to-end. |

**General recommendation:** every contract should carry a unique `id` and, where it's a derived object, a back-reference to the id of the contract it was derived from. This costs almost nothing today and is the difference between "we can trace any trade back to its exact market conditions" and "we can't," which matters enormously for prop-firm audits, debugging, and Performance Analytics.

**No structural changes recommended** — field additions only. This does not violate the frozen-architecture constraint since additive fields don't change any module's logic or the 1:1 passive-transform rule.

